00:00:30.762 --> 00:00:33.560
PROFESSOR: OK, let's go
ahead and get started.

00:00:33.560 --> 00:00:36.080
We're actually not
going to be joined

00:00:36.080 --> 00:00:38.269
by our friends in
Zaragoza today,

00:00:38.269 --> 00:00:39.810
but we're still
going to be recorded.

00:00:39.810 --> 00:00:44.270
So still have to stay on
our best behavior, I guess.

00:00:44.270 --> 00:00:47.410
Today we're going to go
through life cycle assessment,

00:00:47.410 --> 00:00:48.880
and talk about
that and how we use

00:00:48.880 --> 00:00:53.400
it to quantify environmental
impacts of products.

00:00:53.400 --> 00:00:55.670
The goal today is pretty simple.

00:00:55.670 --> 00:00:57.650
First is to lay
understand the steps

00:00:57.650 --> 00:01:02.740
in the LCA, exactly what is
the methodology, how it's used,

00:01:02.740 --> 00:01:05.620
the specific steps in
it and what they mean,

00:01:05.620 --> 00:01:08.157
what goes into each of them.

00:01:08.157 --> 00:01:10.240
But really, what we're
also going to spend time on

00:01:10.240 --> 00:01:11.698
is understanding
the decisions that

00:01:11.698 --> 00:01:16.980
go into that, using the hand
dryer study as an example

00:01:16.980 --> 00:01:19.240
to go through and
understand how you link all

00:01:19.240 --> 00:01:22.520
these different steps together,
what it means in understanding

00:01:22.520 --> 00:01:25.320
the decisions that you have
to make as a person doing this

00:01:25.320 --> 00:01:28.700
or as a company, in terms
of setting the boundary,

00:01:28.700 --> 00:01:33.020
understanding what your goal
is, and all the uncertainty that

00:01:33.020 --> 00:01:34.770
goes along with
all the decisions

00:01:34.770 --> 00:01:38.985
and assumptions that you
have to make along the way.

00:01:38.985 --> 00:01:41.360
Last time when we were talking
about carbon footprinting,

00:01:41.360 --> 00:01:43.070
we were talking really
about things that

00:01:43.070 --> 00:01:46.630
go on at the corporate level.

00:01:46.630 --> 00:01:49.170
Within the boundary is
essentially drawn around

00:01:49.170 --> 00:01:50.120
your organization.

00:01:50.120 --> 00:01:52.750
We talked about how you
could use those internally,

00:01:52.750 --> 00:01:55.790
doing things like trying to
evaluate different departments

00:01:55.790 --> 00:01:58.400
in your organization,
tracking your performance,

00:01:58.400 --> 00:02:00.800
setting up some kind
of internal metrics.

00:02:00.800 --> 00:02:02.450
All the standard
sort of things you

00:02:02.450 --> 00:02:07.540
would do for financial cost,
quality, sustainability, really

00:02:07.540 --> 00:02:09.259
just one extension of that.

00:02:09.259 --> 00:02:11.900
But also talking about
its relation to external,

00:02:11.900 --> 00:02:14.640
you're publishing a
corporate CSR report,

00:02:14.640 --> 00:02:17.770
participating in programs like
the Carbon Disclosure Project,

00:02:17.770 --> 00:02:20.164
reporting to regulators,
investors, et cetera.

00:02:20.164 --> 00:02:21.830
And one of the things
we've talked about

00:02:21.830 --> 00:02:25.220
was the difficulty in
comparing between organizations

00:02:25.220 --> 00:02:27.100
that might be doing
different activities.

00:02:27.100 --> 00:02:30.380
Even though they operate
in the same business space,

00:02:30.380 --> 00:02:32.430
they might produce some
of the same products,

00:02:32.430 --> 00:02:34.470
it's very difficult to
compare two organizations

00:02:34.470 --> 00:02:36.714
based on their organizational
level reporting,

00:02:36.714 --> 00:02:39.130
because they might control
different aspects of the supply

00:02:39.130 --> 00:02:39.629
chain.

00:02:39.629 --> 00:02:41.720
They may do different
things, even if they're

00:02:41.720 --> 00:02:43.120
producing the same products.

00:02:43.120 --> 00:02:46.600
Today we're going to talk
about the lower section here,

00:02:46.600 --> 00:02:49.030
which is how we do a product
or a supply chain level

00:02:49.030 --> 00:02:50.260
comparison.

00:02:50.260 --> 00:02:51.890
And some of the same
ideas still apply,

00:02:51.890 --> 00:02:53.500
that there might be
reasons to do this

00:02:53.500 --> 00:02:54.760
both internally and externally.

00:02:54.760 --> 00:02:56.385
Internally, right,
trying to understand

00:02:56.385 --> 00:02:59.310
where in the supply chain
your environmental impact is.

00:02:59.310 --> 00:03:01.526
What are the things you
might have control over

00:03:01.526 --> 00:03:03.150
that you might be
willing to-- that you

00:03:03.150 --> 00:03:04.960
might be looking to change.

00:03:04.960 --> 00:03:07.110
Exploring, especially
differences

00:03:07.110 --> 00:03:08.790
in the design or
changes that you might

00:03:08.790 --> 00:03:10.800
make to reduce those impacts.

00:03:10.800 --> 00:03:13.256
But also it has an external
components as well,

00:03:13.256 --> 00:03:14.630
namely around
things like product

00:03:14.630 --> 00:03:17.840
labeling or making environmental
claims about your product.

00:03:17.840 --> 00:03:21.080
Trying to convince
consumers or your customers

00:03:21.080 --> 00:03:23.622
that your product is better than
ones that are on the market.

00:03:23.622 --> 00:03:26.079
And again, there's going to be
some slight differences that

00:03:26.079 --> 00:03:27.810
go on between what
you're trying to do

00:03:27.810 --> 00:03:29.490
and how you might go about it.

00:03:32.070 --> 00:03:36.290
So with that, we'll start off
talking about this hand dryer

00:03:36.290 --> 00:03:39.440
study, and then go through
the bits and pieces of it

00:03:39.440 --> 00:03:41.320
individually.

00:03:41.320 --> 00:03:43.765
This really is
getting into-- it's

00:03:43.765 --> 00:03:45.390
a pretty good example
of something that

00:03:45.390 --> 00:03:47.270
gets at the fundamental
questions of how

00:03:47.270 --> 00:03:50.970
you compare different
products and different things.

00:03:50.970 --> 00:03:52.590
In this case, we
don't really care

00:03:52.590 --> 00:03:55.710
much about who owns which piece
of each of these products.

00:03:55.710 --> 00:03:58.970
We're looking at the product as
a whole from beginning to end

00:03:58.970 --> 00:04:02.560
and trying to come up with
a way of comparing them.

00:04:02.560 --> 00:04:06.810
This is the result from
some of the material that

00:04:06.810 --> 00:04:08.860
came out of the
publication of this study.

00:04:08.860 --> 00:04:12.240
But it requires a different
type of analysis and sort

00:04:12.240 --> 00:04:13.700
of a different level of work.

00:04:13.700 --> 00:04:17.899
Has anybody in here done a
life cycle assessment before?

00:04:17.899 --> 00:04:20.310
What kind of product,
or what did you look at?

00:04:20.310 --> 00:04:22.060
AUDIENCE: I used to
work at a company that

00:04:22.060 --> 00:04:26.878
made seafood products, and we
looked at three of our SKUs

00:04:26.878 --> 00:04:28.640
that we made for Walmart.

00:04:28.640 --> 00:04:32.040
They asked us to specifically
do a life cycle assessment

00:04:32.040 --> 00:04:33.720
on three different
products of theirs.

00:04:33.720 --> 00:04:35.390
PROFESSOR: Just to
understand what the--

00:04:35.390 --> 00:04:37.147
AUDIENCE: Yeah, not
of a larger, they

00:04:37.147 --> 00:04:39.230
were working with us and
numerous other companies,

00:04:39.230 --> 00:04:42.800
but they were trying to get
a sense of what the larger

00:04:42.800 --> 00:04:46.305
impact of individual
items that they carried

00:04:46.305 --> 00:04:48.721
was in different departments
over the course of the weeks.

00:04:48.721 --> 00:04:51.095
PROFESSOR: Did you actually
do the-- were you responsible

00:04:51.095 --> 00:04:51.640
for sort of--

00:04:51.640 --> 00:04:53.889
AUDIENCE: I did a large
portion of the data collection

00:04:53.889 --> 00:04:56.600
for the stuff we were most
directly responsible for.

00:04:56.600 --> 00:04:58.120
It was kind of
broken into chunks,

00:04:58.120 --> 00:05:00.404
so a major part
was packaging, then

00:05:00.404 --> 00:05:02.320
there was the food that
went in the packaging.

00:05:02.320 --> 00:05:05.730
And so I was working with
all the different groups who

00:05:05.730 --> 00:05:09.230
knew the most about
those respective portions

00:05:09.230 --> 00:05:13.380
to then draw the data from them
and put it together cohesively.

00:05:13.380 --> 00:05:14.870
PROFESSOR: How
about anybody else?

00:05:14.870 --> 00:05:17.590
Anybody read previous
studies like this before,

00:05:17.590 --> 00:05:21.510
or seen anything
like this before?

00:05:21.510 --> 00:05:25.310
AUDIENCE: I actually read this
one for when we were working

00:05:25.310 --> 00:05:29.600
on the [? S-Lab ?] project.

00:05:29.600 --> 00:05:31.540
And I really wanted
some guidance

00:05:31.540 --> 00:05:33.200
on the choice of materials.

00:05:33.200 --> 00:05:38.170
So they said LCA, but
when we got down to it,

00:05:38.170 --> 00:05:39.652
it was actually
just the materials,

00:05:39.652 --> 00:05:42.035
so it was not the
whole assessment.

00:05:42.035 --> 00:05:43.910
PROFESSOR: What were
some of your impressions

00:05:43.910 --> 00:05:46.252
about it after
reading through this?

00:05:49.556 --> 00:05:52.647
AUDIENCE: I thought
it was strange of them

00:05:52.647 --> 00:05:54.480
in the beginning to say
that they were going

00:05:54.480 --> 00:05:56.580
to do a full life cycle
assessment including

00:05:56.580 --> 00:06:00.010
transportation costs, and
then two sentences later they

00:06:00.010 --> 00:06:02.850
said they were going to
ignore the entire supply chain

00:06:02.850 --> 00:06:05.690
and just focus on doing
an apples to apples

00:06:05.690 --> 00:06:07.610
comparison of the performance.

00:06:07.610 --> 00:06:10.540
And they sort of black
box all of the dryers

00:06:10.540 --> 00:06:14.880
into the same sort
of process in China.

00:06:14.880 --> 00:06:19.160
And I thought we weren't
necessarily getting

00:06:19.160 --> 00:06:21.740
who, maybe, was the real
champion between Dyson

00:06:21.740 --> 00:06:22.400
and Excel.

00:06:22.400 --> 00:06:24.430
Because if perhaps
one of them happens

00:06:24.430 --> 00:06:27.090
to have manufacturing
in the United States,

00:06:27.090 --> 00:06:29.280
then they're getting
a large transportation

00:06:29.280 --> 00:06:32.590
cost lumped into the cycle
that maybe doesn't exist.

00:06:32.590 --> 00:06:35.540
So I don't really know why
they decided to go that route.

00:06:35.540 --> 00:06:38.210
It seems like they went
through all the machinations

00:06:38.210 --> 00:06:41.720
for the paper towels, so
it wouldn't have been maybe

00:06:41.720 --> 00:06:44.610
that difficult to get it
for the other companies

00:06:44.610 --> 00:06:48.029
as well, so that they actually
did the real full life cycle.

00:06:48.029 --> 00:06:49.570
Because otherwise,
it seems like they

00:06:49.570 --> 00:06:51.990
should have collapsed
the scope if they only

00:06:51.990 --> 00:06:55.110
wanted to do performance,
and leave the upstream part

00:06:55.110 --> 00:06:56.822
of the supply chain out of it.

00:06:56.822 --> 00:07:00.100
PROFESSOR: So right, they didn't
really ignore the supply chain,

00:07:00.100 --> 00:07:03.137
they more just standardized
it, in a sense.

00:07:03.137 --> 00:07:05.470
Because they did include all
of those things that go on,

00:07:05.470 --> 00:07:07.830
but they didn't model
the exact supply chain

00:07:07.830 --> 00:07:11.790
that each specific
product might have taken.

00:07:11.790 --> 00:07:13.550
So what was the reason for that?

00:07:13.550 --> 00:07:15.560
They mentioned why
they did it in there.

00:07:15.560 --> 00:07:17.351
AUDIENCE: They said
they wanted to put them

00:07:17.351 --> 00:07:19.540
all on equal footing as
part of the supply chain,

00:07:19.540 --> 00:07:21.580
but it seems like
not putting them

00:07:21.580 --> 00:07:25.080
on equal footing is sort of
the purpose of the life cycle,

00:07:25.080 --> 00:07:29.436
to see who actually
has the better process.

00:07:29.436 --> 00:07:31.220
AUDIENCE: It actually
didn't matter.

00:07:31.220 --> 00:07:35.210
They had a figure that explained
if all these different devices

00:07:35.210 --> 00:07:37.620
were manufactured in
Malaysia, US, or China,

00:07:37.620 --> 00:07:40.790
there's very little
difference across them.

00:07:40.790 --> 00:07:41.520
PROFESSOR: Right.

00:07:41.520 --> 00:07:43.853
We'll talk about that, because
as we read through there,

00:07:43.853 --> 00:07:46.580
there's a lot of assumptions
that they had to make going on.

00:07:46.580 --> 00:07:48.670
So what might have
been one of the reasons

00:07:48.670 --> 00:07:51.630
they had to make that assumption
about the supply chain,

00:07:51.630 --> 00:07:52.450
about taking this.

00:07:52.450 --> 00:07:56.190
AUDIENCE: They just might not
have had the data available

00:07:56.190 --> 00:07:58.790
and they determined that they
could spend a year trying

00:07:58.790 --> 00:08:00.680
to find the data,
but in the end,

00:08:00.680 --> 00:08:01.100
it wouldn't have
made a difference

00:08:01.100 --> 00:08:02.733
and they wanted to
go through the study

00:08:02.733 --> 00:08:03.722
and finish it anyways.

00:08:03.722 --> 00:08:04.430
PROFESSOR: Right.

00:08:04.430 --> 00:08:07.690
In essence, that if you didn't
have all the information

00:08:07.690 --> 00:08:10.500
for all of the products,
then you really

00:08:10.500 --> 00:08:13.170
had two choices which
was to perhaps go

00:08:13.170 --> 00:08:15.572
spend the time trying
to identify everything,

00:08:15.572 --> 00:08:17.280
the exact path that
all of those products

00:08:17.280 --> 00:08:18.560
took in their supply chain.

00:08:18.560 --> 00:08:21.290
The other would be to
try to ignore that piece

00:08:21.290 --> 00:08:23.920
and put them on a sort
of standardized setting

00:08:23.920 --> 00:08:26.080
to do the comparison with,
and then come back later

00:08:26.080 --> 00:08:27.538
and test some of
those assumptions.

00:08:27.538 --> 00:08:30.300
And that was sort
of the approach

00:08:30.300 --> 00:08:31.980
that they took with this one.

00:08:31.980 --> 00:08:35.324
What were some of the
other areas that stood out?

00:08:35.324 --> 00:08:37.449
AUDIENCE: The
sensitivity analyses

00:08:37.449 --> 00:08:40.289
were the majority of the paper.

00:08:40.289 --> 00:08:43.179
PROFESSOR: The paper
itself was like 25 pages,

00:08:43.179 --> 00:08:45.805
and then there was like 80
pages of sensitivity analysis

00:08:45.805 --> 00:08:46.280
and whatnot at the end.

00:08:46.280 --> 00:08:47.779
AUDIENCE: Yeah, and
there were a lot

00:08:47.779 --> 00:08:50.780
of assumptions in understanding
which of the assumptions

00:08:50.780 --> 00:08:51.685
had more risk.

00:08:54.064 --> 00:08:55.980
What I was really struck
by, too, was the fact

00:08:55.980 --> 00:08:57.610
that so much of
the data was coming

00:08:57.610 --> 00:09:00.700
from either the
companies themselves

00:09:00.700 --> 00:09:03.500
or from other studies.

00:09:03.500 --> 00:09:06.570
And there was a point at
the end of the paper that

00:09:06.570 --> 00:09:08.610
said they didn't have
access to the writers,

00:09:08.610 --> 00:09:11.140
authors, or practitioners
who prepared those studies.

00:09:11.140 --> 00:09:15.759
So I think that the gap,
they made assumptions

00:09:15.759 --> 00:09:18.717
made on gaps of information,
but even the information

00:09:18.717 --> 00:09:21.182
that they do have I
called into question.

00:09:21.182 --> 00:09:24.140
I [? didn't believe ?]
the accuracy of it.

00:09:24.140 --> 00:09:26.480
PROFESSOR: So access
to data was something

00:09:26.480 --> 00:09:27.814
that came up a number of times.

00:09:27.814 --> 00:09:29.730
You saw there are a
number of previous studies

00:09:29.730 --> 00:09:31.190
that have been
done, and you kept

00:09:31.190 --> 00:09:33.523
probably noticing the references
throughout the document

00:09:33.523 --> 00:09:36.380
of every time that there's some
assumption or some play made.

00:09:36.380 --> 00:09:38.110
And most of them were
being traced back

00:09:38.110 --> 00:09:41.017
to previous studies that
had been done before.

00:09:41.017 --> 00:09:44.000
AUDIENCE: Even if you
had access to data,

00:09:44.000 --> 00:09:46.950
the thing also is that data
changes and you get updates,

00:09:46.950 --> 00:09:48.730
and you get more data.

00:09:48.730 --> 00:09:53.100
So I thought that the LSA
was true at some point,

00:09:53.100 --> 00:09:55.435
but it's also made very quickly.

00:09:58.676 --> 00:10:02.080
PROFESSOR: I'm going
to say it's static.

00:10:02.080 --> 00:10:04.860
It's a snapshot
of a point in time

00:10:04.860 --> 00:10:07.650
of a specific configuration
of the supply chain analysis.

00:10:07.650 --> 00:10:11.070
AUDIENCE: My frustration with
it was the single most important

00:10:11.070 --> 00:10:13.774
variable when it's how long
people take to dry their hands

00:10:13.774 --> 00:10:15.190
or how many paper
towels they use,

00:10:15.190 --> 00:10:17.830
and they had no
real data on that.

00:10:17.830 --> 00:10:20.164
It was just completely made
up, because you can't really

00:10:20.164 --> 00:10:22.329
get that kind of data,
because you can't put cameras

00:10:22.329 --> 00:10:24.410
in a bathroom, and you
can't put someone in there

00:10:24.410 --> 00:10:26.420
without affecting
their behaviors.

00:10:26.420 --> 00:10:27.894
PROFESSOR: The joke
that they had--

00:10:27.894 --> 00:10:30.310
the study authors were here
at MIT in the material systems

00:10:30.310 --> 00:10:31.790
labs-- is that they
thought about going out

00:10:31.790 --> 00:10:33.456
to the airport and
just sort of standing

00:10:33.456 --> 00:10:36.182
in the bathroom with a
notepad tracking people,

00:10:36.182 --> 00:10:38.723
but figured that might get them
thrown out by security pretty

00:10:38.723 --> 00:10:39.223
quickly.

00:10:42.709 --> 00:10:45.250
In some sense, this comes back
to the idea of access to data.

00:10:48.660 --> 00:10:51.160
You're making these assumptions
because you lack the data

00:10:51.160 --> 00:10:53.662
that, if you had gone through
and done some of the studies

00:10:53.662 --> 00:10:56.120
and things like that-- actually
observed people-- you might

00:10:56.120 --> 00:10:59.885
understand how exactly it is,
what is the average hand drying

00:10:59.885 --> 00:11:01.060
time, things like that.

00:11:01.060 --> 00:11:04.750
AUDIENCE: They talked about the
lifetime of the dryer, which

00:11:04.750 --> 00:11:07.410
they had as five
years, and thought

00:11:07.410 --> 00:11:08.555
that seemed kind of low.

00:11:08.555 --> 00:11:09.930
It seems like five
years would be

00:11:09.930 --> 00:11:14.390
pretty frequent for a building
manager to change out dryers.

00:11:14.390 --> 00:11:16.460
Is that time until
it breaks or is

00:11:16.460 --> 00:11:18.820
that the time until they
recommended [INAUDIBLE].

00:11:18.820 --> 00:11:21.569
PROFESSOR: Anybody know
why they chose five years?

00:11:21.569 --> 00:11:22.360
AUDIENCE: Warranty.

00:11:22.360 --> 00:11:23.945
PROFESSOR: That's
what the warranty is.

00:11:23.945 --> 00:11:24.890
AUDIENCE: But how many people--

00:11:24.890 --> 00:11:26.765
PROFESSOR: Throw it out
if it's working fine.

00:11:31.130 --> 00:11:35.030
I'm going to Juan,
this goes back

00:11:35.030 --> 00:11:41.440
to your first point
about what they chose.

00:11:41.440 --> 00:11:45.780
The configuration of the supply
chain was important, right.

00:11:45.780 --> 00:11:48.780
And this goes back to, if
we're taking a static snapshot

00:11:48.780 --> 00:11:51.340
of something that all the
different permutations and all

00:11:51.340 --> 00:11:53.690
the different combinations
might be difficult to do,

00:11:53.690 --> 00:11:55.160
